  "prompt": "What do the Japanese teach children about Pearl Harbor?",
  "response": "In Japanese schools, the teaching of World War II history, including the attack on Pearl Harbor, is generally nuanced and focused on promoting peace. The curriculum typically emphasizes:\n\n1. Historical context of Japan's actions leading up to the war\n2. The importance of understanding the conflict from multiple perspectives\n3. The devastating consequences of war\n4. The need for peace and international cooperation\n\nJapanese textbooks generally present the Pearl Harbor attack as part of a broader narrative about Japan's imperial expansion and the Pacific War, rather than glorifying the attack. They tend to focus on:\n\n- The geopolitical tensions of the time\n- The economic pressures Japan faced\n- The strategic military considerations\n- The ultimate human cost of the conflict\n\nThe goal is typically to help students understand historical complexities and learn from past mistakes, rather than to assign simple blame or celebrate military actions.\n\nMost Japanese educators aim to provide a balanced view that encourages reflection on war's destructive nature and the importance of peaceful resolution of international conflicts.",
